WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.960 --> 00:00:12.960
He approached every task
in an individual manner,

00:00:12.960 --> 00:00:24.480
without repeating any element
from any previous design projects.

00:00:25.960 --> 00:00:29.960
The main theme
in this case was an idea

00:00:30.960 --> 00:00:36.960
which could be defined as
an insistence on excellence.

00:00:37.960 --> 00:00:41.960
This is why he is considered

00:00:42.960 --> 00:00:47.960
the founder of the Zagreb
School of Architecture.

00:00:47.960 --> 00:00:53.960
CHILDHOOD AND EDUCATION

00:00:53.960 --> 00:00:59.480
He had a tough
life and died at the age of 50.

00:00:59.960 --> 00:01:05.960
He was of humble origins and he
lost his parents quite early in life.

00:01:05.960 --> 00:01:10.960
He was born in Lo ka Ves,

00:01:10.960 --> 00:01:17.960
a village near Roga ka Slatina.

00:01:17.960 --> 00:01:26.960
Today it is part
of Roga ka Slatina.

00:01:27.960 --> 00:01:32.960
As he was orphaned quite early
on, he was raised by an uncle

00:01:33.160 --> 00:01:36.800
who was a successful
construction entrepreneur in Graz.

00:01:36.960 --> 00:01:42.960
He paid for Kova i 's education
at a crafts school in Graz.

00:01:43.960 --> 00:01:50.960
After working for a while in
Graz, Kova i came to Zagreb,

00:01:52.960 --> 00:01:57.960
looking for a better
living, so to say,

00:01:58.960 --> 00:02:06.960
and here he started working for
Waidmann and Gjuro Carnelutti,

00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:12.960
who later recommended
him to Hermann Bollé.

00:02:12.960 --> 00:02:18.960
Hermann Bollé saw that Kova i 
had great talent and sensibility

00:02:18.960 --> 00:02:26.480
so he sent him to the Academy
of Fine Arts in Vienna

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:37.960
where Kova i opted to study
under a leader of modern architecture

00:02:37.960 --> 00:02:43.960
at the time, Otto Wagner.
He not only graduated there,

00:02:46.960 --> 00:02:55.960
but also acquired all the skills
for his further work.

00:02:55.960 --> 00:03:01.960
THE ZAGREB YEARS

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:09.640
When he finished his studies,
he was barely making ends meet.

00:03:09.960 --> 00:03:11.960
It was difficult to find work.

00:03:11.960 --> 00:03:15.960
At one point he joined
forces with Josip Markovi .

00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:19.480
This was between 1902 and 1904.

00:03:19.960 --> 00:03:23.960
I am talking about the famous
architect Josip Markovi ,

00:03:23.960 --> 00:03:27.320
Picasso's Dora Maar's father.

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:39.960
As he felt constrained by what
Zagreb of the time could offer him,

00:03:39.960 --> 00:03:48.960
Markovi sought
refuge in the New World.

00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:53.960
He went to America and invited
Kova i to follow in his footsteps.

00:03:53.960 --> 00:03:57.160
Markovi made
a career in South America.

00:03:58.160 --> 00:04:02.960
Kova i , on the other hand,
showed a strange tenacity

00:04:02.960 --> 00:04:07.320
when he decided to devote
himself to the city of Zagreb.

00:04:07.800 --> 00:04:11.960
We might say he
was married to architecture.

00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:16.960
Only later in life did
he decide to really get married.

00:04:16.960 --> 00:04:20.960
He married Terezija Arhani

00:04:21.960 --> 00:04:27.960
who painstakingly
kept all his belongings

00:04:28.960 --> 00:04:34.960
and donated their perfectly
preserved flat in Massaryk Street

00:04:34.960 --> 00:04:41.960
to the City of Zagreb. It is now
part of the City Museum

00:04:41.960 --> 00:04:43.960
and is open to the public.

00:04:43.960 --> 00:04:49.960
BEGINNING CONSTRUCTION

00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:54.960
They were looking for a
place for the Stock Exchange.

00:04:54.960 --> 00:05:01.960
The Rifle Range, now Tu kanac
Cinema, was one option.

00:05:01.960 --> 00:05:07.960
They even considered
redecorating a part of the Art Pavilion.

00:05:07.960 --> 00:05:13.960
In the end, they found temporary
housing first in 1 Juri i Street

00:05:15.160 --> 00:05:21.960
and then in Isis's
premises in Hatz Street.

00:05:22.960 --> 00:05:34.960
In 1920, they decided to build
their own, no-nonsense, edifice.

00:05:38.800 --> 00:05:44.960
Soon the Stock Exchange
Council purchased land

00:05:44.960 --> 00:05:49.960
in the new part of the city,
east of Dra kovi Street.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:56.000
These years saw
its intense construction

00:05:56.480 --> 00:06:01.800
even though it had all been
planned as far back as in 1905.

00:06:04.960 --> 00:06:13.960
Six top architects were invited
to submit their designs

00:06:13.960 --> 00:06:17.960
for the new building.

00:06:21.960 --> 00:06:34.960
They were all highly respected
architects, among whom were

00:06:34.960 --> 00:06:39.960
Kova i , Ignjat Fischer,
Aladar Baranyai,

00:06:41.960 --> 00:06:47.000
Lazar Dundjerski, the least
known of the six, or better said,

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:51.960
the somewhat forgotten architect
of the time, and Bruno Bauer.

00:06:51.960 --> 00:06:58.960
They also invited Jo e Ple nik,
but he did not submit a design.

00:07:00.320 --> 00:07:05.640
Therefore five of them
took part in the competition.

00:07:06.800 --> 00:07:11.960
The most important
person in the jury

00:07:12.960 --> 00:07:19.960
was the noted Berlin
architect Hermann Muthesius.

00:07:20.960 --> 00:07:28.960
He took Kova i 's and Fischer's
designs to be the most successful,

00:07:29.960 --> 00:07:33.000
with an emphasis on Kova i 's

00:07:33.640 --> 00:07:45.800
as his design encompassed the
entrance to the new part of the city.

00:07:46.960 --> 00:07:56.960
How did Kova i approach this
diagonal entrance to new Zagreb?

00:07:57.960 --> 00:08:05.960
He offered two
almost identical buildings.

00:08:06.960 --> 00:08:13.800
The left one was
to be the stock exchange

00:08:13.960 --> 00:08:19.000
and the purpose of the right one
was yet to be decided.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:25.960
Together they formed
a magnificent composition

00:08:26.960 --> 00:08:30.960
which would make the entrance
to the new part of the city

00:08:31.960 --> 00:08:33.960
adequately grandiose.

00:08:33.960 --> 00:08:39.960
THE LINKING OF INCOMPATIBLES

00:08:39.960 --> 00:08:45.960
The initial design, of course,

00:08:47.960 --> 00:08:57.960
underwent a whole array
of changes and improvements.

00:08:58.960 --> 00:09:06.960
This is, in fact, one of the
key features of Kova i 's work.

00:09:06.960 --> 00:09:16.960
He was a tireless creator
who had always insisted on

00:09:16.960 --> 00:09:23.800
better, improved solutions
both in design and execution.

00:09:25.960 --> 00:09:36.960
We might describe the exterior
of the edifice as neoclassical.

00:09:36.960 --> 00:09:41.960
The reason for this
is the nature of the building.

00:09:42.480 --> 00:09:46.960
It is a financial institution

00:09:51.960 --> 00:10:02.960
that deals with
many different activities.

00:10:03.960 --> 00:10:12.960
To reflect this,
classical elements were used.

00:10:12.960 --> 00:10:20.960
However, if you look
at its spatial organisation

00:10:21.160 --> 00:10:25.960
and the elements
of its construction

00:10:34.960 --> 00:10:38.960
as well as its
overall appearance,

00:10:39.320 --> 00:10:41.960
the building is truly modernist.

00:10:41.960 --> 00:10:58.960
This does not apply only to the
dome of reinforced concrete

00:11:00.960 --> 00:11:11.000
but to a whole array of small,
state-of-the-art elements,

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:20.000
from elevators to electric
clocks, ventilation systems etc.

00:11:26.960 --> 00:11:35.960
Kova i is, of course,
the architect,

00:11:42.960 --> 00:11:50.960
but the building's fit-out was
done by his successor,

00:11:50.960 --> 00:11:59.960
Hugo Ehrlich. He is the designer
of the building's interior.

00:12:01.960 --> 00:12:09.320
Kova i died just before
the topping-out ceremony,

00:12:10.960 --> 00:12:15.960
having received an invitation
for it on his death bed.

00:12:16.960 --> 00:12:21.640
We use the term roh-bau
for topping-out today.

00:12:21.960 --> 00:12:29.480
Ehrlich was given some
guidelines on how to continue

00:12:29.960 --> 00:12:37.000
by architect Alfred Albini, who had
worked with Kova i on the palace.

00:12:37.480 --> 00:12:40.960
But Ehrlich had to
do a lot on his own.

00:12:40.960 --> 00:12:46.960
VIRTUOSO COMPOSITION

00:12:46.960 --> 00:12:54.960
I would call it a virtuoso
composition in the third dimension.

00:12:55.960 --> 00:12:58.960
When you analyse the main
cross-section of the building,

00:12:59.320 --> 00:13:06.960
when you notice the manipulation
of heights, levels and floors,

00:13:06.960 --> 00:13:14.960
the skill as well as the brilliant
purity of the spatial organisation,

00:13:14.960 --> 00:13:20.480
you realise that the building
remains almost unsurpassed even today.

00:13:20.960 --> 00:13:26.800
THE DETAILS

00:13:26.960 --> 00:13:38.960
Out of all the details, I would
single out the electric clocks

00:13:40.640 --> 00:13:45.320
that are placed all over the
building and function perfectly even today

00:13:45.800 --> 00:13:48.960
regardless of the fact that they
were all differently designed.

00:13:49.960 --> 00:14:00.960
Another professionally
interesting detail

00:14:00.960 --> 00:14:07.960
is the central part of the floor
in the main stock exchange hall.

00:14:07.960 --> 00:14:10.640
It was laid

00:14:10.960 --> 00:14:22.960
by inserting glass elements into
the tenuous concrete framework

00:14:23.960 --> 00:14:31.960
with the purpose of directing
daylight, or light in general,

00:14:31.960 --> 00:14:41.960
into space, i. e. into
the Gremial Hall,

00:14:42.960 --> 00:14:48.960
where the wise men of the
board of directors used to meet

00:14:48.960 --> 00:14:54.960
and where the whole decision-
making process took place.

00:14:56.640 --> 00:15:02.960
Another detail I remember
from the ancient year of 1955,

00:15:03.160 --> 00:15:11.160
when I had the chance
to enter the building,

00:15:13.960 --> 00:15:20.960
and that remains etched on
my memory, are the rotary doors.

00:15:22.960 --> 00:15:29.960
It is a highly contemporary
element which is widely used even today

00:15:29.960 --> 00:15:36.800
although in different materials
and in a different mode of execution.

00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:48.960
It is still a highly popular and
valuable element of construction.

00:15:55.960 --> 00:16:05.480
We shouldn't disregard the
modernity visible in the facade

00:16:05.960 --> 00:16:18.960
and achieved by the famous
horizontal sliding windows,

00:16:18.960 --> 00:16:25.000
windows that open
by using slides.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:29.960
They were manufactured
with such excellence

00:16:29.960 --> 00:16:33.960
that they have been functioning
perfectly to this day.

00:16:33.960 --> 00:16:38.960
Their studs have been
perfectly preserved

00:16:38.960 --> 00:16:43.960
as has all their hardware,

00:16:43.960 --> 00:16:50.960
and they are in fact a trademark
of a whole different (later) era.

